<div id="block-views-14f9b5b99cfee6b192e1831674815b66" class="block block-views contributor-info-block">

    
  <div class="content">
    
<div class="view view-contributor-page view-id-contributor_page view-display-id-contributor_block view-dom-id-72633cb3fea665d29e1d5e85a0702e44">
          
    
    
    
      <div class="view-content">
        <div class="contributor-block">
      
  <div class="views-field views-field-field-contributor-image">        <div class="field-content"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-src="https://cdn.road.cc/sites/default/files/styles/medium_avatar_image/public/skinny-banana-2.jpg" src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAMAAAACCAQAAAA3fa6RAAAADklEQVR42mNkAANGCAUAACMAA2w/AMgAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" loading="lazy" class="lazyload" itemprop="image" width="480" height="480" alt=""></div>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-field-twitter-account">        <div class="field-content"><a href="https://twitter.com/roadcc" rel="nofollow"><i class="fa fa-twitter"></i></a></div>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-field-contributor-name">        <div class="field-content"><a href="/content/contributor/john-stevenson" class="h5">John Stevenson</a></div>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-field-contributor-biography">        <div class="field-content"><p class="intro">John Stevenson wrote about bikes and cycling for over 30 years after discovering that people were mug enough to pay him for it rather than expecting him to do an honest day's work.</p>
<p>He was heavily involved in the mountain bike boom of the late 1980s as a racer, team manager and race promoter, and that led to writing for Mountain Biking UK magazine shortly after its inception. He got the gig by phoning up the editor and telling him the magazine was rubbish and he could do better. Rather than telling him to get lost, MBUK editor Tym Manley called John’s bluff, and the rest is history.</p>
<p>After that, John worked on MTB Pro magazine and was the editor of Maximum Mountain Bike and Australian Mountain Bike magazines, before switching to the web in 2000 to work for CyclingNews.com. Along with road.cc founder Tony Farrelly, John was on the launch team for BikeRadar.com and subsequently became editor-in-chief of Future Publishing’s group of cycling magazines and websites, including Cycling Plus, MBUK, What Mountain Bike and Procycling.</p>
<p>John also wrote for Cyclist magazine, edited the BikeMagic website and was founding editor of TotalWomensCycling.com before handing over to someone far more representative of the site's main audience.</p>
<p>John died from cancer on 4 May 2025. He changed his name to John Abbott Valentine shortly before his death, after reconnecting with the family of his biological father. </p>
</div>  </div>  </div>
